1 Effect of mother’s lifestyle on newborn infant appearance

Lifestyledata = opt %>%
  select(c("BMI", "Use.Tob", "Use.Alc", "Drug.Add", "Apgar1"))
head(Lifestyledata)

Note that a BMI over 25 corresponds to at least overweight and an Apgar1 under 7 is considered as low.

1.1 BMI vs Apgar1

Let’s start by looking at the distribution of BMI when the Apgar1 is low and when it is normal.

lowApgar1_BMI = Lifestyledata %>%
  filter(BMI != "NA", Apgar1 < 7) %>%
  pull(BMI)

normalApgar1_BMI = Lifestyledata %>%
  filter(BMI != "NA", Apgar1 >= 7) %>%
  pull(BMI)

Drug_table = Lifestyledata %>%
  filter(Apgar1 != "NA", Drug.Add == "No " | Drug.Add == "Yes") %>%
  select(c("Drug.Add", "Apgar1")) %>%
  mutate(Apgar1 = case_when(Apgar1 >6 ~ "Normal", TRUE ~ "Low")) %>%

There should be only 2 values: Yes and No. The third value is not an empty string but something like ” ” but we don’t know how many space there are.

alc_table =Lifestyledata %>%
  filter(Apgar1 != "NA", Use.Alc == "No " | Use.Alc == "Yes") %>%
  select(c("Use.Alc", "Apgar1")) %>%
  mutate(Apgar1 = case_when(Apgar1 >6 ~ "Normal", TRUE ~ "Low")) %>%
  table() 
alc_df = tibble(
  Score = c("Low", "Normal"),
  Count = c(alc_table[3], alc_table[6])
)

no_alc_df = tibble(
  Score = c("Low", "Normal"),
  Count = c(alc_table[3], alc_table[6])
)
blank_theme <- theme_minimal()+
  theme(
  axis.title.x = element_blank(),
  axis.title.y = element_blank(),
  panel.border = element_blank(),
  panel.grid=element_blank(),
  axis.ticks = element_blank(),
  plot.title=element_text(size=14, face="bold")
  )

#Source: http://www.sthda.com/english/wiki/ggplot2-pie-chart-quick-start-guide-r-software-and-data-visualization
alc_pie = alc_df %>%
  ggplot() +
  aes(x = "", y = Count, fill = Score)+
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  ggtitle("Consume Alcohol") +
  coord_polar("y", start = 0) +
  #scale_fill_brewer("Blues") +
  theme_void()


no_alc_pie = no_alc_df %>%
  ggplot() +
  aes(x = "", y = Count, fill = Score)+
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  ggtitle("Do not consume Alcohol") +
  coord_polar("y", start = 0) +
  
  blank_theme

gridExtra::grid.arrange(alc_pie, no_alc_pie, ncol =2)

We can change the number of square, maybe 100 is too much. Here is an exemple in a 4x10 “waffle” :

(Non_Smoker_low_2 = round(40 * Tobacco_table[2]/(Tobacco_table[2]+Tobacco_table[5])))
## [1] 3
(Smoker_low_2 = round(40 * Tobacco_table[3]/(Tobacco_table[3]+ Tobacco_table[6])))
## [1] 3
w1 =waffle(c("Low" = Non_Smoker_low_2, "Normal" = 40-Non_Smoker_low_2), 
           title = "Non-Smokers ", colors = c("#4169E1", "#00BFC4")) 
w2 =waffle(c("Low " =Smoker_low_2, "Normal" = 40-Smoker_low_2), 
           title = "Smokers ", colors = c("#4169E1", "#00BFC4"))
gridExtra::grid.arrange(w1, w2, ncol =2)

3 Smoking vs birthweight

newdf = opt %>% 
  filter(BL.Cig.Day != "NA", Birthweight != "NA") %>%
  select(c(cig = BL.Cig.Day, Birthweight)) %>%
  mutate(cig = as.double(cig), Birthweight = as.double(Birthweight)) %>%
  mutate(smoke_status = case_when(cig >= 9 ~ "High", cig <9 ~ "Normal"),
         Birth_status = case_when(Birthweight < 2500 ~ "Low", Birthweight >=2500~ "Normal")
         ) %>%
  group_by(smoke_status, Birth_status) %>%
  summarize(Count = n())
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'smoke_status'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
newdf
newdf %>%
  ggplot() +
  aes(x = smoke_status, y = Count, fill = Birth_status)  +
  xlab("Smoking Activity") +
  ylab("") +
  labs(fill = "Birthweight") +
  geom_bar(position = position_fill(reverse = TRUE), stat = "identity") +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent)  +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("#4169E1", "#00BFC4"))

tabchisq = as.table(cbind(c(10,34), c(4,44)))
chisq.test(tabchisq, correct = FALSE)
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  tabchisq
## X-squared = 3.6865, df = 1, p-value = 0.05485
smokedf = opt %>% 
  filter(BL.Cig.Day != "NA", Birthweight != "NA") %>%
  select(c(cig = BL.Cig.Day, Birthweight)) %>%
  mutate(cig = as.double(cig), Birthweight = as.double(Birthweight), 
         Birth_status = case_when(Birthweight < 2500 ~ "Low", Birthweight >=2500~ "Normal"))
finaltob = opt %>% mutate(cig = case_when(Use.Tob == "No " ~ 0,
                               Use.Tob != "No " ~ as.double(BL.Cig.Day)
))
tobdf = opt %>% mutate(cig = case_when(Use.Tob == "No " ~ 0,
                               Use.Tob != "No " ~ as.double(BL.Cig.Day))) %>% 
  filter(cig != "NA", Birthweight != "NA") %>%
  mutate(smoke_status = case_when(cig >= 9 ~ "High", cig <9 ~ "Normal"),
         Birth_status = case_when(Birthweight < 2500 ~ "Low", Birthweight >=2500~ "Normal")
         ) %>%
  group_by(smoke_status, Birth_status) %>%
  summarize(Count = n())
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'smoke_status'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
tobdf
